He tells us (p. 72.) that one of the Fines they must Pay, who are in Imployment, is to have their Conduct Censured by the Standers by. This is very true, and there is no help for it; for some discontented Persons, for want of other Business, are frequently employed in finding fault with others, and this Author has given us an Instance of this Practice in his Third Discourse, in which (amongst all his formal Schemes and seeming Demonstrations) he has proved nothing more plainly, than that his main Design was to Magnifie the good Conduct of the first Commissioners, (of which number himself was on
                  •
               ) and to Censure the Conduct of the several Commissioners who have since been intrusted with the Management of that Revenue: This will appear from the high Encomiums he gives of the first Commissioners and their Management, and from what he Suggests concerning the latter.
